AB  - Landscape simulation can be a good means to understand the observed evolutions to then identify the factors generating the changes. We have worked on the evolution of the land use in a " commune " in the chain of the Puys, by using a model dealing with the ecological growth of vegetation that agricultural practices hinder. The discrete event simulations enable to study long-term evolutions and take space aspects into account, but farm modelling is still simplistic. We have then developed a multi-agent model that enables us to take into account the interactions between the farms subjected to competition and synergy. This work corroborates that a multi-agent modelling is quite adapted to study the influence of social relationship on the territory and then on the landscape. In this presentation, we also show how a multi-agent model can be integrated to discrete event simulations.
